Dynamic Optimal Dealing Range
Instead of anchoring to base 0, anchor the midpoint of the Goldbach Fib to the daily fix price (the asset's daily settlement/reference price). For NQ this is calculated from the last 30 seconds before 16:00 ET. This acts as a price magnet throughout the session.
PO3 Stop Runs
Two forms:

Liquidity Stop Run: Stops resting beyond an old high/low are swept by a PO3-sized move (3, 9, 27 pips), triggering a reversal
Wick Stop Run: Price creates a candle wick of exact PO3 size at a Goldbach level — validates the Rejection Block

Rule of thumb: For a 729 PDR, look for PO3-2 (81-point) stop runs outside the range. For stop runs inside smaller ranges, 3 or 9 pip wicks are common.
STDV PO3 Levels
From the daily fix price, project PO3-sized standard deviation lines above and below. These act as intraday S/R for scalpers (every 27 handles for NQ scalping, every 81 handles for intraday).
PO3 Liquidity
Price often stops a PO3 number short of a Goldbach level, leaving a "liquidity pocket":

A 3-pip gap short of a level may require a 9-pip stop run to clear it
Liquidity appears as: gaps of PO3 size, order blocks of PO3 size, or swing lows/highs a PO3 distance short of a Goldbach level

Paradigm: Goldbach level → untouched → short-term low/high forms above/below it (PO3 size) → liquidity run clears it using a PO3 stop run.
