What Is the Look Back Partition?
A time-based system using multiples of 9 (the Tesla Vortex) to define monthly anchor points throughout the year. Each partition marks the start of a new ~30-day window for seeking a major price reversal.
The Sequence & Monthly Calendar
Starting from 18, add 9 each time. Skip 9 and 90. Split the result: leading digits = month, last digit = day:
NumberMonthDayLook For18January8th18-pip stop run/gap/OB27February7th27-pip36March6th36-pip45April5th45-pip54May4th54-pip63June3rd63-pip72July2nd72-pip81August1st81-pip99September9th99-pip108October8th108-pip117November7th117-pip126December6th126-pip

If the date falls on a weekend, use the following Monday.
Look back window = 20–60 days (1–3 prior partitions).

How to Use Look Back Partitions

At the start of each partition, identify the partition number (e.g., 108 for October)
Look for a clue in the previous 1–3 partitions: a stop run, FVG, or order block of exactly that pip size
Expect price to hit this clue during the first few trading days of the new partition
After the clue is hit, expect an opposite PO3 stop run (reversal signal)
Price returns to the partition's trading range after the reversal

Goldbach Time (GBT) for Look Backs
Add the day number + month number. When the sum equals a Goldbach number, that's a GBT anchor day.

GBT 11 (day + month = 11): Expect the look back clue to be hit on this day. Example: January is month 1, so day 10 = 1+10 = 11 → look back clue hits January 10th.
After the GBT 11 clue hit, expect the reversal/stop run 11 or 17 days later.

HIPPO (Hidden Interbank Price Point Objective)
A HIPPO is a "hidden" order block formed from 2 consecutive candles that both create FVGs:

Connect the top wick of candle 1 to the bottom wick of candle 2 → reveals a hidden zone
HIPPOs frequently form around:

CE (Consequent Encroachment) levels
Non-Goldbach levels (23/77 and 35/65)
These become trigger points for breakaway and measuring gaps


Like regular OBs, HIPPOs can "invert" — when traded through, they become mitigation levels on a retrace

HIPPO Sensitivity Point: The close of candle 1 / open of candle 2 junction is the most precise S/R within the HIPPO.

